8 review of the general incidente of litigation.

In every action there is some contentiori, allegation, or averment of a plaintiff which is met or encountered by some contentiori, allegation, or averment of a defendant.

The contention of the plaintiff (intentio) is the assertion of some right of the plaintiff : e. g. in a real action, the assertion of do- minion (si paret illam rem Auli Agerii esse): in a personal action, the assertion of an obligation (si paret Numerium Negidium Aulo Agerio illam rem dare facere oportere). In an action with a formula in factum concepta there is an implicit or indirect assertion of a right, although explicitly and directly the intentio only asserts the fact which forms the title on which such right is founded. In the wording of the formula the right of the plaintiff appears as an hypothesis 3 because the formula or instruction to the judex is a hypothetical command, expressed in a sentence of which the intentio forms the antecedent or protasis, and the condemnatio the consequent or apodosis.
